A "league of nations on the pitch": An analysis of overseas players in the English Premier League and their effect¶

Context¶

The English Premier League (EPL) was established in 1992 after the teams making up the then English Football League Division One decided to break away from the Football League, and take advantage of the huge sums of money being offered to them as part of a televised football deal. It was later to become the most-watched sports league in the world, broadcasting to 212 territories, and a potential TV audience of 4.7 billion people. 1

Following the Bosman ruling in 19952 and the fluid international transfer market that it gave birth to, the EPL witnessed an influx of overseas players wanting to compete in this new, exciting league. In 2013, the EPL's own website displayed the following:

"The Barclays Premier League is now the world’s league... It has become a league of nations on the pitch too. In 1992 there were only 11 non-British or Irish footballers in the Premier League. These days there are, on average, around 70 nationalities running on to the pitch in the Premier League." 3

However, this is not seen as a positive by everyone involved with, or following, the EPL. Some believe that this has had a negative effect on the development of indigenous football players; that it has been dentrimental to grassroots football and club academies, where young players are now competing against players from all over the world for that golden ticket - a club contract. Ultimately, many talk of its negative effect on the prospects of the English national team. As a result, the EPL introduced the Homegrown Player Rule for the start of the 2010/11 football season. This initiative stated that each club squad of 25 players must contain at least eight homegrown players. A homegrown player is a player who has been under contract with an English team for at least three years before turning 21. 4

It is my intention to analyse the member teams of the Premier League, and the league itself, since it's inception in 1992, to see how the competition's squads have changed. Was the EPL a "league of nations" by 2013, and how was that different to 1992, and when Liverpool won the Premier League title in 2019/2020? Have those teams that have embraced the overseas transfer market had more success, more than those sides that have attempted to nurture more homegrown talent through their academies. Have clubs in London seen more of an influx of overseas players than, for example, those at the opposite end of the country in the North West? And, finally, is it the names of overseas players that are lauded by teams' fans when they discuss their greatest Premier League goal scorers or creative geniuses?

Premier League data¶

Locating the data¶

Obtaining the Premier League data required for my purposes was not as simple as I first thought. Football data tends to centre around, as one would expect, results, goal scorers, league positions, etc. What I needed was squad information, including key player stats, and - of course - nationality. Further, detailed Premier League information is often not free, it being such a popular league - as discussed earlier - with a lot of website and application opportunities, including those that make money such as gambling sites.

However, after a lot of searching and researching, I came across FBRef, a part of the Sport Reference group of websites that also publish statistics for American Football and Baseball, amongst others 5. Their websites offer extensive and detailed information on all aspects of your searched-for-sport, most imporantly for me, a detailed breakdown of every club's squad players, including nationality, for every EPL season since it's birth in 1992.

How to store the data¶

I soon realised that to perform any kind of successful analysis around the questions that I raised above, I need a lot of data. There have been 28 Premier League seasons, not including the current season (I had decided not to look at the current season as it is ongoing, and therefore any analysis on the effect of non-English players on this competition would be incomplete). The first three seasons of the EPL were contested by twenty-two teams, while season 1995/96, and all subsequent seasons, have had twenty members. I therefore required the player information of 566 Premier League squads (3 seasons of 22 teams, plus 25 seasons of 20 teams).

These 566 squads would have obvious relations - the club they belonged to, and the season in which they competed. This, coupled with the fact that - being a JavaScript developer - I work day-to-day with data in JSON format, made me initially decide upon scraping the data from FBRef and storing it as a JavaScript object, with each season being a primary key, for example:

{ '2008/09': [ { 'club': 'Newcastle Utd', ... } ... '2009/10': [ { 'club': 'Newcastle Utd', ... } ... ] }

At first, this seemed to be a successful way of storing the data. Viewing each individual season was simple, as was drilling down into a team within that season. However, it soon became apparent that while the relationships between a squad member and his team, and the relationship between his team and the season in which it played, where easy to inspect, many relationships were not. Collating a club's squad information for a team across multiple seasons became more difficult; finding the number of French players across all clubs in a season was time consuming; studying any drop of homegrown players from 2010/11 was confusing.

Further, the objects were becoming too big, as I decided to add more and more properties. To test whether playing non-English players had an effect on the success or failure of a team, I needed to store each individual player's statistics - such as goals score, assists, etc - and the player's JSON object, in particular, became complicated and unwieldy.

It was clear, then, that JSON wasn't the answer, and I decided upon the CSV format. Furthermore, to mitigate the loss of my JSON data relationships, I also decided to scrape all of the data into one CSV document, as opposed to multiple documents storing, for example, a single season or individual club. I was confident that, despite it being a large dataset, storing it in CSV would still produce a manageable file size, and I wasn't disappointed when I completed my first web scrape.

Getting the data¶

Those CSV advantages aside, the process, I discovered, was slow. Each squad on the FBRef website is displayed on an individual page - as stated before, on 566 individual pages. Those detailed squad pages have no discernible pattern in their URL, all containing a seemingly random eight character string. The only way to successfully navigate to those pages, therefore, was to follow individual links from each EPL club name in the final position table for each season (all twenty eight seasons). Again, these season pages had no discernible format in their URL and so, again, the only way to navigate to each season was to follow a link from a list of all EPL seasons-to-date on the FBRef Premier League Seasons index page (https://fbref.com/en/comps/9/history/Premier-League-Seasons).

The process, therefore, looked like this:

  1. Load Premier League index page.
  2. Locate required season page hyperlink.
  3. Follow hyperlink and load required season page.
  4. Locate club's squad hyperlink.
  5. Follow hyperlink and load required squad page.
  6. Locate squad player and scrape, clean and save his data.
  7. Repeat step 6 for each player in the squad.
  8. Repeat steps 4 - 6 for each club competing in that season/
  9. Repeat steps 1 - 7 for each season that has been played and completed.

It was clear, then, that I only wanted to carry out these steps when absolutely necessary. As a result, the first time the script was run, the data is saved as a local CSV file. From that point on, we only run through the process of scraping the data if the locally saved CSV file can't be found - we have the luxury of working with data that won't change and therefore the locally saved CSV file won't ever become stale. Further, I set up the local filename in such a way that I could force a new scrape if I so wished, without having to rename, move or delete the most recent file.

After running through the process a number of times, making tweaks to the data I wanted, cleaning it in different ways, removing data points, adding data points, etc, I decided to add some configuration settings to my script. Firstly, anyone running the scraping function can view detailed progress information, giving them an insight on how many seasons, clubs and players have been read, and how many are remaining. def addRowToCSV(file, row):
    with open(file, 'a+', newline='') as file:
        writer = csv.writer(file)
        writer.writerow(row)

Using the principle of separation of concerns, as I had to inspect and scrape seasons, clubs and players, I created a function for each. The following is used to gather all the necessary information for all - or a specific number of - Premier League seasons, found after opening the Premier League Seasons index page:

In [6]:
def getAndCleanSeasons(url, numSeasons):
    # Open the page
    page = urlopen(url).read()
    # Find the table containing all of the Premier League seasons
    soup = BeautifulSoup(page)
    table = soup.find(id='seasons')
    tbody = table.find('tbody')
    # Get the season links
    seasonCells = tbody.find_all('th', attrs={'data-stat': 'season'})
    # Remove the first one as we only want FULL/COMPLETED seasons
    seasonCells.pop(0);
    # How many seasons to analyse?
    totalSeasons = numSeasons if numSeasons <= len(seasonCells) else len(seasonCells)
    seasons = seasonCells[:totalSeasons]
    # Return the required seasons
    return seasons

Next, we need to go into each individual season, after following the link to the season page, and locate each team that competed. Again, we return all teams or a specified amount of teams. We store the season name, and return the name and collected teams for that season.

In [7]:
def getAndCleanSeason(domain, season, numTeams):
    # Get the season name and link
    seasonLink = season.find('a').get('href')
    name = season.text.strip()
    # Open season page
    page = urlopen(domain + seasonLink).read()
    soup = BeautifulSoup(page)
    # Get the results table
    table = soup.findAll('table', id=lambda x: x and x.startswith('results'))
    tbody = table[0].find('tbody')
    rows = tbody.find_all('tr')
    # How many teams to analyse?
    totalTeams = numTeams if numTeams <= len(rows) else len(rows)
    season = rows[:totalTeams]
    # Return the required season and any other needed info
    return {
        'name': name,
        'season': season
    }

Now, within each season, we must inspect each individual team. We store it's final position for the season, and total points. Next, we follow the link to the team page - where we'll find the squad - locate the player, and return all the information we've collected.

In [8]:
def getAndCleanTeam(domain, team):
    # Get the team name
    teamCell = team.find('td', attrs={'data-stat': 'squad'})
    name = teamCell.text.strip()
    # Get their position for that year
    rankCell = team.find('th', attrs={'data-stat': 'rank'})
    rank = int(rankCell.text.strip())
    # Get their points total for that year
    pointsCell = team.find('td', attrs={'data-stat': 'points'})
    points = int(pointsCell.text.strip())
    # Grab the team link
    link = teamCell.find('a').get('href')
    # Open the team page
    page = urlopen(domain + link).read()
    soup = BeautifulSoup(page)
    # Get the squad table
    table = soup.findAll('table', id=lambda x: x and x.startswith('stats_standard'))
    tbody = table[0].find('tbody')
    rows = tbody.find_all('tr')
    # Return the required team and any other needed info
    return {
        'name': name,
        'rank': rank,
        'points': points,
        'players': rows
    }

Finally, we look at each individual player, locating and cleaning all of the required data. We have to be careful at this point as it was found that some of the required data is omitted for certain players in FBRef - nationality, for example. Further, the total minutes that a player played throughout a season was formatted with a comma. I removed this to allow for easy analysis later.

In [9]:
def getAndCleanSquadPlayer (player, cats):
    squadPlayer = []
    for c in cats:
        cell = player.find(attrs={'data-stat': c})
        text = cell.text.strip().encode()
        text = text.decode("utf-8")

        # Some values are missing in the FB tables
        if not len(text):
            text = 0

        if c == 'minutes':
            if not isinstance(text, int):
                text = text.replace(',', '')

        if c == 'nationality':
            # At least one player doesn't have a stated nationality at all...
            if isinstance(text, int):
                text = 'NOT STATED'
            else:
                # ... and some nationalities don't have a flag icon on FB
                if len(text) and ' ' in text:
                    text = text.split(' ')[1]
        
        squadPlayer.append(text)
    
    # Return the required player
    return squadPlayer

Finally, as stated earlier, the scraping process took some time, so I wanted to pass progress infomation back to the screen, so that I could see that everything was working, and have an indication of how near to completion the process was.

In [10]:
def displayProgress(messageVars):
    if int(messageVars['playerCount']) == 1 and int(messageVars['teamCount']) == 1 and int(messageVars['seasonCount']) == 1:
        print('----------- BEGIN -----------')
    message = '-- Getting player {playerCount} of {playersTotal}, from {teamName} ({teamCount} of {totalTeams}), in {seasonName} ({seasonCount} of {totalSeasons}) --'
    print(message.format(**messageVars))
    if int(messageVars['playerCount']) == int(messageVars['playersTotal']) and int(messageVars['teamCount']) == int(messageVars['totalTeams']) and int(messageVars['seasonCount']) == int(messageVars['totalSeasons']):
        print('----------- END -----------')

In [12]:
def getPremierLeagueData():
    
    # Set a flag so we only add the headings when/if we have data...
    # ... and we only add them once!
    headersAdded = False
    
    # Step 1: Open the Premier League Seasons index page
    seasonCells = getAndCleanSeasons(domain + indexPage, numOfSeasonsToAnalyse)
    
    # Set up a season count for the progress display
    seasonCount = 1
    
    # Step 2: Visit each season page
    for seasonCell in seasonCells:
        
        # Pass each row off to the relevant processing function
        seasonData = getAndCleanSeason(domain, seasonCell, numOfTeamsToAnalyse)
        season = seasonData['season']
        seasonName = seasonData['name']
        
        # Set up a team count for the progress display
        teamCount = 1
        
        # Step 3: Visit each team page
        for team in season:
            
            # Pass each row off to the relavant processing function
            eplTeam = getAndCleanTeam(domain, team)
            players = eplTeam['players']
            teamName = eplTeam['name']
            
            # Set up a player count for the progress display
            playerCount = 1
            
            # Visit each squad member
            for player in players:
                
                # Pass each row off to the relavant processing function
                squadPlayer = getAndCleanSquadPlayer(player, playerCats)
                
                if len(squadPlayer):
                    # Add what we already have to the player
                    squadMember = [seasonName, eplTeam['rank'], teamName, eplTeam['points']] + squadPlayer
                
                    # Output progress data
                    if displayProgressWhileScraping:
                        displayProgress({
                            'playerCount' : playerCount,
                            'playersTotal' : len(players),
                            'teamName': teamName,
                            'teamCount': teamCount,
                            'totalTeams': len(season),
                            'seasonName': seasonName,
                            'seasonCount': seasonCount,
                            'totalSeasons': len(seasonCells)
                        })
                    
                    # If we haven't added the CSV headers, do it now
                    if not headersAdded:
                        addRowToCSV(localDataFile, csvHeadings)
                        headersAdded = True

                    # Write row to CSV
                    addRowToCSV(localDataFile, squadMember)
                
                # Increment player for messaging
                playerCount += 1

            # Increment team for messaging
            teamCount += 1
            
        # Increment season for messaging
        seasonCount += 1
        
# Get the Premier League data
if not os.path.isfile(localDataFile):
    getPremierLeagueData()

Other relevant data¶

After collecting the Premier League data, I became aware that the nationalities of each player are shown using the FIFA country code, rather than a more human readable format. As the nationality is so essential to our data, I decided to create a further CSV file that we can use to map the FIFA country code to it's full country name, making our data visualisations more appealing and easier to understand. I create this file by locating the necessary data on the relevant Wikipedia page.

In [13]:
def getFIFICountryCodes():
    countryCodesFile = 'countryCodes.csv'
    countryCodesUrl = 'https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_FIFA_country_codes'
    countryCodes = {}
    
    # Check if we already have countryCodes csv
    if not os.path.isfile(countryCodesFile):
        # No file. Visit wikipedia
        page = urlopen(countryCodesUrl).read()

        # Find the tables containing the codes
        soup = BeautifulSoup(page)
        tables = soup.find_all('table', {'class': 'wikitable'})
        # The final table isn't relevant
        tables = tables[:-1]

        # Visit each table
        for table in tables:
            trs = table.find_all('tr')
            # Wikipedia doesn't use thead some remove header row
            trs.pop(0)
            for child in trs:
                # Get each country and code and add it to dict
                tds = child.find_all('td')
                countryCodes[tds[1].text.strip()] = tds[0].text.strip()

        # Write the dict to a csv
        w = csv.writer(open(countryCodesFile, 'w'))
        for key, val in countryCodes.items():
            w.writerow([key, val])

    else:
        # Have the file, so read it
        with open(countryCodesFile, 'r') as f:
            for line in f:
                s = line.strip().split(",")
                countryCodes[s[0]] = s[1]
    
    return countryCodes

As we can see, the opening season of the Premier League saw 175 overseas (a nationality that is stated as being other than English) players feature in the competition's squads. After a slight drop the following year (to 173), this number increased almost consistently until it hit a high in the 2015-2016 season. We can get a clearer look at the most notable figures like so:

Overseas players as a percentage of total players¶

The above, however interesting, does not give us the full story. What we really need to know is the number of overseas players as a percentage of the players involved in that season. The peak of 415 that we saw in the 2015-2016 season means little if that season saw the largest squad numbers on record for Premier League seasons. Let's see if we can get a more detailed analysis.

This is a little more interesting. What we can now see is that our peak of 415 players in the 2015-2016 season is actually misleading. When we take the number of overseas players as a percentage of all squad players, we find that there have been an incredible 10 seasons in which there was a higher number of overseas players playing in the Premier League. We actually find that it was season 2013-2014 that saw the highest percentage of overseas players run out for Premier League side, when it broke 70% for the first and only time in Premier League history, up to and including last season. We can see by this that the Premier League really has been a magnet for overseas football players. The average percentage of non-English players playing in a Premier League season is a remarkable 57.6%, with the minumum almost 34% in the league's second season, and peaking - as discussed - at just over 70% in 2013-2014.

A "league of nations on the pitch"¶

So we have seen that the Premier League has consistenly fielded a large number of overseas players in it's competition, an average of almost 60% of all it's players. But, as the Premier League itself claimed in 2013, can it be seen as a "league of nations on the pitch". Let's look at how the nations of the world are represented.

Regional Differences¶

The Premier League has had teams compete in it's competition from every corner of England and Wales. From Newcastle to Bournemouth, and from Swansea to Norwich. Have overseas players featured heavily in all regions of England and Wales, or have they played more often in teams based in, for example, London? Let's see if we can find that out.

Firstly, let's take a look at the teams that have featured in the Premier League, and see who have fielded the most overseas players.

Effects - Succcess and failure¶

We have seen that Premier League teams have always fielded a large number of overseas players, and that an incredible amount of nations have been represented in the league. But, other than giving us the opportunity to regularly watch some of the greatest players in the world, what effect has this had on the Premier League and it's teams in terms of success or failure?

To try and answer this question, let's find the team with the highest percentage of overseas players in their squad for each season of the Premier League, and look at their final league position for that season.

In [30]:
# Highlight functions
def highlightRow(s, value, color1, color2, column):
    found = pd.Series(data=False, index=s.index)
    found[column] = s.loc[column] == value
    return [('background-color: %s' % color1) if found.any() else ('background-color: %s' % color2) for v in found]

def highlightLeaguePositions(s, column):
    found = pd.Series(data=False, index=s.index)
    found[column] = s.loc[column] == 1
    return [('background-color: red') if found.any() else ('') for v in found]

These results surprised me. We often think of overseas players as being the most creative, the most naturally gifted players, more adept at reading the game and able to unlock defences. As a result, I expected the above data to be completely dominated by overseas players. Here we see that of the 26 players who have finished the season with the most assists, 18 were overseas players. That's almost 70%. It clearly still has a bias towards overseas players, but it doesn't show the domination that I thought it would.

Let us return to goals. We've seen how many times the Premier League's top scorer has been an overseas player, but that tells us about the league itself - what about the effect, on goals, by overseas players for each individual team? Let's see if we can find out how many teams that have featured in the Premier League can point to an overseas player when hailing their team's most prolific player in the competition.

Conclusions¶

We have seen that overseas players have always been an important, indeed, essential part of the English Premier League.

After 175 overseas players took park in the inaugural season of the Premier League, representing 34% of that season's squad members, the number of overseas players has increased almost consistenly, hitting a peak in the 2013-2014 season when overseas players accounted for a huge 70% of all squad members. If we consider the slight drop in numbers in the league's second season, we can perhaps point to the Bosman ruling in 1995 after which the numbers began to increase. We saw that after the start of the 2010-2011 season, and the beginning of the Homegrown Player initiative, the following two seasons saw a slight drop in the number of overseas players, but that those numbers soon recovered, increasing dramatically for the start of the 2013-2014 season. Finally, we were able to determine that when we look at every club squad for every season of the Premier League so far, the average percentage of non-English players playing in a Premier League season is almost 58%.

Following the Premier League's claim that it was a "league of nations on the pitch", we found that at least 120 countries have been represented in the Premier League, although the strongest represented nations have been close to home, with the Republic of Ireland, Scotland and Wales taking three out of the top four most represented countries. It was seen that Scotland dominated the overseas players market until the turn of the century when an influx of French players pushed their nation to the top, where it stayed for eight consecutive years - Arsene Wenger surely having a part to play in this. We also saw that Spain's numerous successes in international competitions since 2008 has seen it now dominate the overseas players' numbers since 2016.

While the team with the highest number percentage of overseas players in a season has won the Premier League on only three occassions, it was noted that only twice in 28 seasons has a team with the highest percentage finished lower than 14 - although both teams suffered relegation. Delving deeper into these figures, we can see that while Watford finished 13th in 2015-2016 with almost 91% of their players being overseas players, no other team fielding 90+% overseas players has finished lower than a very impressive fourth place.

Examining the spread of overseas players throughout the regions of England and Wales, that have made up the membership of the Premier League, it was found - surprisingly - that it is Wales who have fielded a larger total percentage of overseas players in their squads than any other region. Furthermore, London also sits behind the South East, the West Midlands and the North East in overseas player numbers, despite Fulham having fielded the highest percentage of overseas players, pushing past 70%.

We found that 13 overseas players have been awarded season top scorer - only three of the nine English players who have been good enough to claim that title have won it this century. Of the 26 players who have managed the most assists in a season, only 8 were English players.

Finally, we found that the fans of 22 football clubs look towards an overseas player when they toast their most prolific Premier League goal scorer; and it's 24 clubs who worship an overseas player when looking at arguably their most creative Premier League player, the one who managed the most assists.

Overall, I think what we have found is that one the most compelling reasons that the English Premier League is the greatest in the world is because of its overseas talent. We have been lucky enough to enjoy the best years of players such as Henry, Drogba, Agüero and Bergkamp and witnessed the rise of players like Cristiano Ronaldo, De Bruyne and Salah. That said, this author's bias aside, Alan Shearer remains the Premier League's most prolific and greatest goal scorer.

Further Work¶

To extend the analysis further, it would be interesting to look at minutes on the pitch - have the figures been skewed by overseas squad players who signed contracts with Premier League sides, but then didn't make an impact and failed to make regular appearances?

It might also be compelling to look at player's positions. Have overseas players dominated a particular area of the pitch? Do we see more overseas defenders than overseas midfielders? Do teams field more overseas strikers than they do English strikers? I am struggling to remember a Premier League season when football fans would name an English player when discussing the league's best goalkeeper.

Finally, although I'm unclear where this data could be sourced, I would very much enjoy looking further into the argument that a proliferation of overseas players has damaged grassroots football and made it more difficult for homegrown players to break into Premier League sides. I would like to get the data from Premier League clubs' academies - those that have them - and analyse how they have been affected by the overseas transfer market.
